Observation Details: Two pairs with no chicks. One single male. Single male with a single “teenager” juvenile. Pair with four small chicks with fairly-well-feathered wings, short tails and topknots, and fairly advanced mantle feathering. Pair with four small chicks with fairly-well feathered wings but with very little mantle feathering, and not much tail or topknot. Pair with nine very small chicks with fairly-well-feathered wings but not much tail or topknot. Pair with eleven very small chicks with fairly-well-feathered wings, but not much tail or topknot. Pair with fourteen tiny brand-new, striped fuzzy chicks. Single male with five “teenager” juveniles of advanced age (three juv males, two juv females. This is the first set that was hatched earlier in the year, whose adult female went missing the second day after the brood first appeared. The single male parent, nicknamed “Good Dad”,  has been successfully raising them on his own).

Observation Details: Estimate

This was the only photo-cooperative quail encountered today, calling in a mesquite tree not too far from the NW corner of the ponds. Photo below. Cap bright chestnut with thin black line of demarcation. Breast pale blueish-gray. Belly patch fairly large and essentially black with no scaling. Light patch on breast cream-white with no scaling. Fairly extensive scaling on its sides, but within range of scaling seen in GAQUs. Face and throat basically black; slight hint of gray in forehead is also well within normal variation. Possibly the same GAQU photographed here by others in recent days.

Appears that in me and BJ’s photo of one quail that decided to pose out in the open not far from the rundown yellow house in harsh lighting with the sun directly behind the bird. This bird appears to be a mostly pure male GAQU with very minimal scalings on the breast. Other features favoring GAQU include the dark patch on the belly, and reddish cap. Those photos will be added later. Sounded more like Gambel’s as well. If needed to switch to the hybrid option or just the slash option of the 2 species please let us know as I know this species is very tough and I believe most Gambel’s populations around Borrego Springs have some California Quail traits in them or are actual hybrids.
Two pairs of Gambel's Quail had very young fledglings, one pair had 12 young and the second pair had four young.

A family of nine was in the treed island at the parking lot by the boat ramp. There were two adult males, one adult female and six immatures. They were foraging around a large anthill. The immatures were too old to call Recently Fledged Young but definitely evidence of breeding success.

Observation Details: Two adults and 9 very young chicks. After eating, the adults flew to the top of the block wall expecting the chicks to also fly up onto the wall. The chicks are too small to fly that distance, they remained on the ground. The chicks followed the female around the yard, resting in the shade of a small bush and along the wall. The female gathered the chicks under her wings for they to rest. We opened the gate for the family to leave, they did not. The pattern of the trying to get the chicks to fly to the wall and then resting as a group continued until we stopped watching.

The pattern of the trying to get the chicks to fly to the wall and then resting as a group continued until we stopped watching.
9 chicks

Observation Details: Two males and a female.  None show ventral scaling or speckling/streaking of the nape.  The males' throat patch is more chevron-shaped at the bottom than those of California Quail males, and the white border is thinner, especially at the bottom.  The female's ventral area is characterized by short, thin, sparsely distributed streaks.  Her face doesn't show the streaking/speckling typical of a California Quail.  Note that while the two males are never in the same photo, the pattern of white streaks on the wing coverts of the males are different, so there are, in fact, two.

Appears that in me and BJ’s photo of one quail that decided to pose out in the open not far from the rundown yellow house in harsh lighting with the sun directly behind the bird. This bird appears to be a mostly pure male GAQU with very minimal scalings on the breast. Other features favoring GAQU include the dark patch on the belly, and reddish cap. Those photos will be added later. Sounded more like Gambel’s as well. If needed to switch to the hybrid option or just the slash option of the 2 species please let us know as I know this species is very tough and I believe most Gambel’s populations around Borrego Springs have some California Quail traits in them or are actual hybrids.

Observation Details: (Note - since we always have quail blocks set out year-round, we usually get very high counts at this time of year during baby quail season) Three pairs with no young. Two single males. Several sets of young: 1). Pair with two small chicks, wings well-feathered (everything else downy), 2). Pair with five small chicks, backs and wings feathered, 3). Pair with four mixed-age chicks: two older well-feathered, and two younger less-developed; 4). Pair with fourteen chicks with feathered backs and wings; 5). Pair with eleven “teenage”-sized juveniles; 6). Pair with two fully-feathered mid-sized juveniles; 7). Pair with one tiny new chick; 8). Pair with six mid-sized chicks; 9). Pair with nine well-feathered mid-sized chicks; 10). Single male with five nearly adult-sized immature (three males, two females). [The last set #10 was the first brood hatched in our yard. The female disappeared on day two, and the male has been raising the brood, without losing any, by himself - which earned him the nickname "Good Dad"].

Media notes: Photo shows a few of the members of a mixed-brood of Gambel's Quail that contains older chicks that have already acquired wing feathers, and younger chicks still in mostly natal down.
Observation Details: A pair of Gambel's Quail with a set of fledglings of two different ages: seven of them were older with nearly complete sets of wing feathers and some mantle feathers; and four much younger chicks mostly still in natal down. In the nine breeding seasons I've been closely observing Gambel's Quail in our yard, at least one or two mixed-age broods occur each year. These are not caused, as one might have assumed, by females laying eggs in others' nests (which happens), for in those instances all chicks in a nest that hatch in the same time frame become the final brood, resulting in a virtually same-aged set, indistinguishable from any other full brood. The females simply don't wait around for any delayed eggs to hatch, so if eggs have been inserted into their nest by a second female too late in the setting process, those unhatched eggs are abandoned. Instead, mixed-age broods are normally created when the adults with chicks engage in squabbles and chases around the bird feeding area, often involving several families at a time. Chicks that panic in the melee sometimes get separated while hiding under vegetation, and get left behind. Later in the day they either get "reacquired" by their parents who hear them calling, or sometimes a completely different pair passing through with their own brood. Or sometimes a portion of a brood will simply follow the incorrect parents out of the feeder area, either after mild squabbles, or just because they are not paying attention. The male quails will often attack and peck at non-familial youngsters that attempt to join their brood, usually causing those chicks to readjust and follow the correct parents - but if the correct parents have already gotten too far away, even though still in the same general vicinity, the confused and panicked chicks may persist, causing the non-familial male to just give up, resulting in a mixed brood that goes on their way together. If the mixed brood makes close contact again with the original brood within a reasonably short time, (within a few hours or less) I have observed the "adopted" chicks switching back to become reunited with their correct parents. But if the separation lasts overnight, the mixed brood remains together for the rest of the season as if it were one unit. Even close contact with the original family does not then trigger the "adopted" chicks to return to their original parents. It has certainly been very fascinating watching this particular behavior over the years
